/*
Overriding ‚â† Changing a value

Overriding means replacing inherited behavior at runtime via polymorphism.

Changing a variable value is state modification, not overriding.*/

//Overriding means redefining the same inherited virtual method in a child class to change its behavior.
// actual code here,
class packet;
   int a=7;
  function void post();
    $display("a=%0d", a);
  endfunction 
  
endclass

module tab;
  packet pac=new();
  initial begin
    pac.a=91; // here, override varible
    pac.post();  //
  end
endmodule 
//code is end 
// Great question ‚Äî this is **the exact point where most people get confused** üëç
// Let‚Äôs be **very precise with terminology**.

// ---

// ## ‚ùå This is **NOT overriding**

// ```systemverilog
// pac.a = 91;
// ```

// This is **just assignment**, **not overriding**.

// ---

// ## 1Ô∏è‚É£ Why this is NOT overriding

// ### Overriding requires:

// 1. **Inheritance (`extends`)**
// 2. **Same member name in parent & child**
// 3. **Runtime polymorphism**

// Your code has:

// * ‚ùå No child class
// * ‚ùå No inheritance
// * ‚ùå No polymorphism

// So **overriding cannot even happen** here.

// ---

// ## 2Ô∏è‚É£ What your code is actually doing

// ```systemverilog
// packet pac = new();
// pac.a = 91;
// ```

// üëâ You are simply **changing the value of a public variable** of an object.

// This is equivalent to:

// ```sv
// int x = 7;
// x = 91;
// ```

// No OOP concept involved.

// ---

// ## 3Ô∏è‚É£ Think of overriding like this (very simple)

// | Action                      | Is it overriding? |
// | --------------------------- | ----------------- |
// | Change variable value       | ‚ùå No              |
// | Assign in constructor       | ‚ùå No              |
// | Same variable name in child | ‚ùå No (hiding)     |
// | Virtual method redefinition | ‚úÖ YES             |

// ---

// ## 4Ô∏è‚É£ Compare with REAL overriding (method)

// ```systemverilog
// class base;
//   virtual function void post();
//     $display("base");
//   endfunction
// endclass

// class child extends base;
//   function void post();
//     $display("child");
//   endfunction
// endclass
// ```

// ```sv
// base b;
// child c = new();
// b = c;
// b.post();
// ```

// ### Output

// ```
// child
// ```

// üëâ This is **true overriding**

// ---

// ## 5Ô∏è‚É£ Why language designers disallow variable overriding

// Because:

// * Data members are **compile-time bound**
// * No `virtual` variables
// * Would break object memory layout

// So SystemVerilog **intentionally disallows** it.

// ---

// ## 6Ô∏è‚É£ Correct terminology for your example

// ```sv
// pac.a = 91;
// ```

// ‚úÖ **Modifying a data member**
// ‚úÖ **Runtime assignment**
// ‚ùå **Not overriding**

// ---

// ## 7Ô∏è‚É£ Interview one-liner (VERY IMPORTANT)

// > **Assigning a value to a class variable is not overriding; overriding applies only to virtual methods and requires inheritance and runtime polymorphism.**

// ---

// ## 8Ô∏è‚É£ One-sentence takeaway

// > **Overriding changes behavior via inheritance; assignment changes data, nothing more.**

// ---

